It's exciting. So, I can't make this work, why, yeah .

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:02.820
Yeah, so just a little bit about me. I am the 
chief research and Innovation officer at Funka,

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:08.880
I'm also the representative of the UN initiative 
G3ICT and the International Association of

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:15.000
Accessibility Professionals representative to the 
EU. I do a lot of strategic consulting these days

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:22.080
mainly for the European Union but also for um 
EU member states, national governments, when

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:29.880
they are transposing their the EU legislation 
into national law. Um, I did, I'm leading the Radix

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:35.760
subgroup which is an expert group helping the 
commission and the member states implementing

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:41.460
the web accessibility directive, one of the recent 
legislations in this area, and I'm also one of the

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:49.020
technical experts in the ETSI special task force 
536. And we have been responsible for updating and

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:55.440
harmonizing the EN standard which is the minimum 
requirements of the legislation in in Europe.

00:05:58.020 --> 00:06:04.080
Um, just a couple of words on the, on the 
company I work for - Funka - we are specialists

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:09.720
in accessibility, uh, but we were founded by 
the disability movement in Sweden and we

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:16.380
um, we started as an NGO, really but we
converted into a private company in the year of

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:23.520
2000. We have our headquarters in Stockholm,
and and offices also in Oslo, and Madrid, and

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:30.060
Brussels. We do consulting and development on
accessibility and usability, we do also a lot of

00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:35.820
research and innovation and that's nowadays 
the department that I lead, and so we

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:42.000
do national projects and also European and Global 
projects in research and innovation. And we also

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:48.480
cover policy and and different kind of studies 
and investigations and we are of course also

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:53.340
engaged in standardization, which is extremely 
important if you want to do accessibility. Also

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:57.480
one of the proud founders of the International 
Association of Accessibility Professionals.

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:05.760
So, in Europe, the web accessibility directive 
is really turning everything upside down here.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:10.980
We have been living in a world where we have 
more recommendations on accessibility than

00:07:10.980 --> 00:07:16.740
actual regulations, and this is now changing. 
We started with a procurement directive a

00:07:16.740 --> 00:07:23.760
couple of years ago, now the web accessibility 
directive is covering public sector, and in 2022

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:28.320
we will also have the European Accessibility Act 
which will cover products and services in some

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:35.340
of the private sectors. We are really moving 
from recommendations to, to regulations. And

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:42.000
it's an interesting time to be alive, here, 
but we have a couple of problems when when

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:46.920
this is happening, of course, and um, and 
one of the biggest problems that we have,

00:07:47.640 --> 00:07:53.460
um tried to to solve or looked into at least, is 
that really, really that accessibility is much

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:58.980
more than a technical issue, of course, and 
around 50 percent of the accessibility problems or

00:07:58.980 --> 00:08:05.700
fails that we encounter when we do audits - they 
are created by web authors. And this is not a

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:11.640
surprise, because many web authors - and this is 
now in in public sector mainly - and most of the

00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:18.180
web authors are not professional communication 
people, and absolute vast majority of them are

00:08:18.180 --> 00:08:23.640
not accessibility experts. So, of course they do 
create content that is not perfectly accessible.

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:32.160
And, and this means that we now have approximately 
7 million interfaces that are supposed to, to

00:08:32.160 --> 00:08:37.620
comply with the new regulations and with seven 
million interfaces we have, I don't know I can't

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:42.420
even count the number of web authors that would 
need training to, to make this work. And of course

00:08:42.420 --> 00:08:46.620
that's good for us, because we are specializing 
in this, and we're happy to provide training, but

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:52.740
it just won't scale. It's not enough just to put 
out manuals and training and, and you know trying

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:59.880
to make all these web authors do the right thing,
because it, people change their job, they, um they

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:05.520
get on [parent leave, parental leave or or 
you know, we change people all the time. So we just

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:09.780
need to do something else than only training, 
because that, that is not, will never be enough.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:16.800
And that's when, when the idea came that - what if 
accessibility could be built into the websites

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:22.080
from the start? What if the authoring tools could 
do something to help, here? Um, maybe everything

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:28.500
can't be automized, but at least the authoring 
tools should have a possibility to give much

00:09:28.500 --> 00:09:33.960
better support to the web authors. That was sort 
of the idea behind this, this research projects.

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:41.280
And we managed to lobby for this idea and make 
more people interested in it, and after a while

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:47.880
the European commission came out with a, with a 
call for, um, for proposals on trying to see if

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:55.860
authoring tools could actually, uh, be part of 
the solution here. So, um, the European funding

00:09:55.860 --> 00:10:02.760
for research, and very common way of doing this, 
is that you first, you apply for a pilot project,

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:09.120
where you sort of prove that your idea or thesis is 
valid, and that there is something here to, to keep

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:15.180
um, looking into, and then, if you're successful in 
your pilot, then you can also have the possibility

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:19.320
to make what is called a preparatory action. 
Which is where you actually perform the real

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:25.740
research or, or whatever initiative is needed 
to be done. So it's a two-step process, often .

00:10:26.820 --> 00:10:34.020
and um we did get the opportunity to have a, to 
perform a pilot project a couple of years ago ,

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:40.920
where we looked at the 30 most used tools in the 
public sector bodies in in the EU. So we, we crawled

00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:46.740
the internet for public sector bodies and, and 
found the 30 most used tools, to make sure that we,

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:54.600
um, the efforts were made on the most frequently 
used ones. And we did some piloting and testing, so

00:10:54.600 --> 00:10:59.700
trying to see what happens if you, if you're not 
an expert in accessibility, and you're procuring

00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:04.980
this tool, and maybe your, your supplier is 
also not an expert in accessibility, because

00:11:04.980 --> 00:11:12.360
that is the normal case - that is the majority of 
these situations. What happens then? If you just

00:11:12.360 --> 00:11:17.460
acquire an authoring tool and a website for 
somebody, from somebody that is not an expert,

00:11:18.060 --> 00:11:23.580
how accessible is it then? It's like, I know this is 
really theoretic, because it's not really possible,

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:28.260
but the idea is if you just sort of push the 
button and up comes a website from your package

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:34.320
then how accessible is it by default. What 
is built-in there. And the answer was: not much.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:42.780
But we did a lot of surveys and prototypes, we 
talked to, uh to suppliers and, and vendors and tool

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:47.940
makers, and so on, try to figure out how much is 
really included in the, sort of, basic, the standard

00:11:47.940 --> 00:11:53.460
templates, and so on. And we did a lot of analysis 
and also user testing, of course. User testing both

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:59.040
with web authors, and also end users with, with 
disabilities to, to make sure that the results

00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:05.700
were valid from both perspectives. And we did also 
work a lot with different stakeholders in, and that

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:12.600
this was before the Corona so we, we could make, um 
physical workshops in Brussels. We had specific, uh

00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:19.020
webs, workshops with web authors from public sector, 
to see what are the user needs; how can the authoring

00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:24.360
tools help these web authors to, to make 
the right thing. It should be easy to, to do the

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:29.700
right thing when you create content. And we also 
discussed with the end users with disabilities

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:35.880
of course, which are the most common problems or 
fails, or what is the biggest barrier to you .

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:44.760
And also looking into the, the back office, so to 
speak, so if if the Web author has a disability, how

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:52.020
accessible is the actual interface that you meet 
as, as author. So the, the back end, so to speak, the

00:12:52.020 --> 00:12:58.200
input part of the of the authoring tools. And then 
we also discussed with the tool makers and other

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:04.020
vendors, suppliers, and also standardization bodies. 
So we had a series of workshops where we, where we

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:10.080
really collected user needs and experiences 
from this for different stakeholder groups.

00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:17.220
And the result from this pilot was that, well, there 
is not much accessibility by default out there in

00:13:17.220 --> 00:13:24.540
the most used tool, unfortunately, but they're big 
demand. And also we thought that there would be, um

00:13:24.540 --> 00:13:30.240
well, a good potential to do something. If something 
is not perfect, then you have the the potential

00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:37.860
to, to make it better. So, the result of the pilot 
was really a matrix of, of the most used tools.

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:44.400
And also we made three sets of guidelines for web 
authors, or people who are procuring or looking for

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:50.520
a tool, and also for end users with disabilities, 
and for the industry. And really this was then the

00:13:50.520 --> 00:13:58.140
starting point for further research. And the result 
of this um, on the part, the open parts and not

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:02.940
everything is, is public, but the public parts of 
this project results can be found on our website.

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:14.880
It's www.funka, which is f-u-n-k-a.com slash we4authors. 
So "we" and the number 4, and "authors."

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:23.100
And then, of course, the next phase started and 
we were happy enough to, to get also the second

00:14:23.100 --> 00:14:31.140
phase funded by the commission. And we are now, uh 
a third into, um the preparatory action which

00:14:31.140 --> 00:14:35.700
is called "we4authors cluster" and here we, we 
work with a cluster of tool makers, because we

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:42.900
think we need now to dig deep into the the real 
code and the real, um potential of this. So, based

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:48.720
on the user needs that we found in the pilots, 
and we are going to create new features that

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:56.220
can be adapted into whatever tool you use. We 
are going to do extensive user testing to make

00:14:56.220 --> 00:15:02.580
sure that the features that we create are really 
good - they're user friendly, they are solving the

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:08.820
right problems, and that the web authors like them. 
Because otherwise they won't be a success. And we

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:14.160
are then going to try to implement these features 
in different kinds of tools, so that we make sure

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:21.060
that we can reach as big part of the market as 
possible. And, and we are then, when the project

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:27.000
is finished, by July next year, we are going to 
share code, if there, if we are resulting in code,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:32.700
which I hope, or, if we can't produce the code, 
then at least we will share the documentation,

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:40.020
and prototypes, videos, visits, or whatever it can be 
from the user testing, to show as inspiration for

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:46.740
others. Because maybe everything can't just be a 
snippet of code, and then you can just implement it

00:15:46.740 --> 00:15:52.920
quickly into whatever tool, maybe life is not that 
easy, always, so we will also describe the feature,

00:15:52.920 --> 00:15:58.140
and describe how it works, and what people liked 
with it. And so that then, the rest of the market

00:15:58.140 --> 00:16:05.820
can, hopefully, use those ideas and for inspiration, 
and also implement these ideas in their own tools.

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:15.540
And this is really an important part of of, of 
all European research, of course, that, that the

00:16:15.540 --> 00:16:21.540
result is going to be for the common good. So this 
is not something we, or the partners, will, will keep

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:25.920
um, behind any closed doors - the idea is, 
is really to share with the community.

00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:36.600
And the members of this cluster, right now, 
are Drupal, um, we have um Mike Gifford of Open

00:16:36.600 --> 00:16:43.380
Concept who is representing Drupal, here. We 
have Plone, represented by Timo Stollenwerk from

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:51.120
kitconcept, in Germany. We have SiteVision, 
a Swedish licensed, um licensed-based authoring

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:58.380
tool. We have Joomla, um, and Brian Teeman is the 
representative for Joomla, and the foundation of

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:05.700
Joomla in Germany, it's also a part of the project. 
And we have Umbraco, represented by Sigma in the UK.

00:17:06.600 --> 00:17:11.820
So, these are the cluster members who are 
representing different kind of, of authoring

00:17:11.820 --> 00:17:18.360
tools. And we are, of course, also working with other 
tool providers, and, but we are also closely related

00:17:18.360 --> 00:17:22.560
to the International Association of Accessibility 
Professionals, so that we can reach out to both

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:32.160
vendors, and also, um, customers using these tools, 
and the end user organizations. So, with IAAP we,

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:38.700
we have a really broad outreach, apart from, from 
the partners own networks, so to speak, and we also

00:17:38.700 --> 00:17:45.360
work closely with ERRIN, which is the European 
Regions Research and Innovation Network. So, in

00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:53.160
with this network we can also make sure that 
we reach a lot of the public sector bodies' web

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:59.640
authors in, in Europe for user testing and, and 
also making sure that the user requirements are,

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:03.420
are met in a really, uh, relevant way for them.

00:18:06.060 --> 00:18:12.120
After the discussions with, with the 
stakeholders and the different user groups, and

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:18.900
specifically, of course, the web authors, their 
needs, and also the ideas and experiences from our

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:25.260
cluster members, so, to make sure that whatever we 
do is, is sort of relevant, and possible to use also

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:34.860
for the tool makers, we have, we set up a set of 
criteria for, for how the features would; what

00:18:34.860 --> 00:18:43.560
kind of um, what kind of problems we wanted to, to 
solve, how frequently this um, problem was occurring,

00:18:43.560 --> 00:18:48.840
and so on. And then, based on these criteria we 
selected 10 different features that we wanted

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:57.600
to try with users. So now we are, specifically, in 
the position in the, in the project where we are,

00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:03.240
we have already selected 10 features, and we are 
now going to user test them, starting in October.

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:10.320
um so we are, right now, finishing or refining 
the prototypes, that we are then going to, to

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:17.460
test in an iterative process, of course, inviting 
users, web authors, and others interested to test

00:19:17.460 --> 00:19:22.620
the prototypes and come with, come back to us with 
feedback, so that we can refine them, and make them

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:29.040
better and better. So, we have until Christmas to do 
this, really, but we're starting here in October. So

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:37.500
the features that we have, um, selected to try and 
make sure that we can support users, web authors

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:45.120
with, is really how to provide alt text -alternative 
text -on, on images. It's a very basic thing but

00:19:45.120 --> 00:19:50.880
we have seen that this is solved in different ways, 
in different authoring tools, and sometimes it's

00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:57.420
quite hard to make it in a good way, and sometimes 
it's, well, you have the possibility to add the alt

00:19:57.420 --> 00:20:02.940
text, but you don't get any support on how to write 
it, or when to write it on or when not, and so on. So

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:08.760
the whole idea here is to provide more support. 
If something can be, maybe, mandatory we will try

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:13.740
to make it mandatory. Alt texts can't really be 
mandatory, because not all images need them, and

00:20:13.740 --> 00:20:20.820
so on, but we can also prompt for the Web author 
to do something, so it's really visible, it's really

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:28.320
um, you're sort of pushed to do the right 
thing. You shouldn't be, um, you shouldn't have

00:20:28.320 --> 00:20:33.960
to look for the place where to write the alt text. 
It should be very obvious and sort of "in the flow"

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:42.720
of your authoring process. And then the, we 
can also provide, maybe, support in different, at

00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:49.920
different levels, or information. So we have all 
this sort of the levels of, of automation we can

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:54.960
do - we can either build it in, so that it's really, 
by default, making it accessible; or we can prompt

00:20:54.960 --> 00:21:01.680
it, or we can make information, or, or support in 
in other ways. So we will try different ways of

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:08.640
doing this, and see what the web authors find most 
useful, and then present that to, to the market, when

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:16.260
we have a good decision there. So alt text is the 
first one, and then we are also prototyping now the

00:21:16.260 --> 00:21:22.320
possibility to change language, um, when you have 
a multiple language on a, on a website or a page,

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:30.000
which is very common in, in the European context. 
We often have websites with, with more than one

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:36.120
language. Also, we're looking at documentation of 
the accessibility features, because our research

00:21:36.120 --> 00:21:41.340
has shown that many web authors don't really know 
what their authoring tool can do. So how can we

00:21:41.340 --> 00:21:47.220
make the documentation better, and also, how can we 
make it, or we want to try, if it's better to have

00:21:47.220 --> 00:21:53.220
the documentation - the information -that support 
in a wizards, sort of "in context," so where you

00:21:53.220 --> 00:21:58.200
are actually performing, doing something, that is 
when, where you can find the information. Or, if

00:21:58.200 --> 00:22:04.380
that may be disturbing for you, because the user 
experience will be then, maybe, too crowded, or too

00:22:04.380 --> 00:22:09.120
overwhelming with all this information. So, maybe 
it's better to have it sort of on the side, that

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:14.340
you need to go look for it. And we have we have 
seen different situations, different contexts, and

00:22:14.340 --> 00:22:20.280
also different Web author groups who prefer one or 
the other, so this will be really interesting to do

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:28.920
AB testing on. Um, of course some of the really big 
troublemakers in authoring is tables and forms, so

00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:37.200
we are going to test supportive tables creators 
and also forms editors in different way, that can

00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:43.440
um, a combination of making it accessible by 
default, and supporting on when you do more

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:48.180
complex tables and forms. Of course, everything 
can't be automated, or at least not now,

00:22:49.140 --> 00:22:54.540
um, maybe in the future, but we want to to 
make sure that the author has better support,

00:22:55.440 --> 00:23:02.580
uh, in doing the right thing. When it comes 
to video, we are testing supporting

00:23:02.580 --> 00:23:06.900
the editor on how to make sure that the 
video is compliant with the regulations.

00:23:08.100 --> 00:23:13.260
And then we have four features that are sort 
of connected to each other, and they all have

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:21.120
to do with testing. So we want to try out 
how to best test accessibility while, or

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:31.560
when you are editing or publishing something. 
So we are trying to have testing procedures built

00:23:31.560 --> 00:23:37.920
into the editor, so while you're actually creating 
the content. And then another specific sort of

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:46.920
easy win if, if we support web authors in, in 
providing accessible documents. Especially,

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:53.280
specifically PDF documents which is, all over the 
world, I think we have unaccessible or inaccessible

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:59.700
um documents, and that is a a big issue that 
many web authors tell us they would like to

00:23:59.700 --> 00:24:05.220
have support in. So, some kind of testing before you, 
or while you're uploading your documents, so that

00:24:05.220 --> 00:24:11.460
you know if the document is okay or not. And then 
we want to test the full page. So when you have

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:18.840
um, provided all the images, and the objects, and 
the content that you are going to to publish,

00:24:18.840 --> 00:24:24.900
then during this content creative, creation 
phase, you could also test all the different

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:31.920
parts and objects that you are, um, going to, to 
publish. So before publishing just check if it's

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:36.720
accessible or not, and then, of course, helping 
you to remediate this will be an important part.

00:24:37.380 --> 00:24:43.500
And maybe not specifically for the Web author, 
but for the website owner, or the person who is

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:50.700
responsible for the whole, accessibility, um, 
the accessibility of the whole website, then

00:24:51.300 --> 00:24:55.620
of course there could also be a 
built-in testing tool for the whole website.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:25:01.980
And please note that we are not building a new, eh, 
automatic tools for accessibility testing. There

00:25:01.980 --> 00:25:06.180
are many out there and some of them are really 
good. So we are not going to test if they are

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:13.440
good or bad, it's just the how can they be combined, 
or included, or implemented, in the authoring tool

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:20.640
or in the content creation phase, so that it 
supports the, the web authors in a better way.

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:26.700
Because what we see is that many of the testing 
tools are quite technical. And they may be very

00:25:26.700 --> 00:25:32.520
helpful for developers, but the web authors are 
sometimes not very technical, so it can't be too,

00:25:33.660 --> 00:25:38.700
um, sort of, success criteria related and 
really technical in the way it's presented.

00:25:38.700 --> 00:25:43.800
It needs to, to support you in, in another 
way. And we think combining it into the

00:25:43.800 --> 00:25:49.560
content creation phase could be really 
helpful for at least some other web authors.

00:25:50.220 --> 00:25:55.740
So these are the 10 features that we are now 
prototyping, and going to test, and these are going

00:25:55.740 --> 00:26:03.540
to be test like generic tests, and so that we have 
made them anonymous, so to speak, so we are trying

00:26:03.540 --> 00:26:09.420
to just test the feature it, and the prototypes are 
not supposed to look like any specific tool, but

00:26:11.220 --> 00:26:19.020
it wouldn't, it shouldn't be important which 
tool you're used to use, but you should be, sort of,

00:26:19.020 --> 00:26:27.000
recognizing the, the content creation, how it looks 
when you, when you edit content. That is the, the

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:33.420
idea. So, we're doing, um, this testing on a prototype 
level, and then when we, when we have learned more

00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:40.500
or less what the web authors need or or want, then 
we're also going to do test implementations in the

00:26:40.500 --> 00:26:46.800
cluster members. So all the authoring tools that 
are working with us in this project also have the

00:26:46.800 --> 00:26:56.760
possibility to, to test the, these features in their 
own, um, in the technical environments, so to

00:26:56.760 --> 00:27:04.500
speak. Of course it takes time to implement these 
things in authoring tools and, and maybe we won't

00:27:04.500 --> 00:27:09.900
be finishing this before the project is finished, 
but at least we want to make sure that we have

00:27:09.900 --> 00:27:16.620
done some test implementations, so that we can also 
say that we know that these, these features work

00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:21.840
in at least some of the technical environments 
that we have tested, because that makes it more

00:27:21.840 --> 00:27:27.480
probable that they will also be possible to use 
for other tool makers. So the test implementation

00:27:27.480 --> 00:27:33.600
in the specific tools is also an important part. 
But what we are trying, doing right now is first

00:27:33.600 --> 00:27:40.440
of all the generic testing. And because of the 
pandemic we will do, we will do some face-to-face,

00:27:41.820 --> 00:27:48.180
um, physical testing at our offices, but most of 
the testing, so, the quantitative part of it will

00:27:48.180 --> 00:27:54.420
be online. So it's actually open for anyone that 
would like to, to test these features and we are

00:27:54.420 --> 00:28:01.740
happy to welcome anyone. And we'll come back to 
that. So, um, will this solve all the accessibility

00:28:01.740 --> 00:28:08.040
problems of the world? No, it won't. But we believe 
that built-in accessibility by default in

00:28:08.040 --> 00:28:14.160
authoring tools could be an important part of 
the solution. If we succeed in this. Um, because,

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:20.040
I mean, this is kind of obvious, but if you, if the 
authoring tool is supporting you in your content

00:28:20.040 --> 00:28:25.920
creation phase, then you can avoid unnecessary 
mistakes. And this is really the primary goal here.

00:28:27.180 --> 00:28:32.820
Um, accessibility by default can make it. We can, 
we can start with the hygiene factors that the

00:28:32.820 --> 00:28:36.480
authoring tools shouldn't, sort of, create 
accessibility problems, but it should also

00:28:36.480 --> 00:28:42.780
support the author in not doing that mistakes. 
Another important part here is really to

00:28:42.780 --> 00:28:47.880
help the non-experts to get it right from the 
start. Because, as I mentioned before, most of the

00:28:48.600 --> 00:28:54.000
web authors in public sector are, are not 
specializing in communication, and definitely

00:28:54.000 --> 00:29:00.720
not specializing in accessibility. So we also hope 
that this can mean that the governments can create

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:06.960
framework contracts, so in the centralized 
procurement that is very use, much in use

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:15.300
in, in some of the European member states, which 
can mean that tool makers that do provide

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:21.660
accessibility by default using our features or,
or other services, but, but some, in some way can

00:29:21.660 --> 00:29:28.920
prove that they, they do provide good support for 
web authors, they can then have a, um, an advantage

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:35.040
in the competition, by being sort of checked on 
beforehand by, by the central procurement system.

00:29:35.700 --> 00:29:40.560
So that is what we're hoping. That a group of 
tools will be, sort of, the front runners here, and

00:29:40.560 --> 00:29:45.600
they will then have the possibility to easier 
at least sell their services to public sector.

00:29:47.940 --> 00:29:56.040
And with that, experts in accessibility, and also 
experts in, in tool making can, and the web authors

00:29:56.040 --> 00:30:01.320
themselves can, focus on more interesting things, 
or more complex issues, and sort of solving the

00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:07.500
rest of the problems that we can't solve in this 
problem. But that is the, that is the aim of these

00:30:07.500 --> 00:30:15.780
projects. So, I would like to invite you all 
to make contact to us and if you are like to, or

00:30:15.780 --> 00:30:21.360
if you, one of your clients or customers would like 
to try, if you have any web authors, if you know web

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:26.520
authors that would like, are interested in trying 
out these features, then please do contact us.

00:30:27.120 --> 00:30:31.740
There is room for everyone who wants to, to 
contribute to this, and of course the more test

00:30:31.740 --> 00:30:36.360
persons we have, from the more parts most part 
of the world, and with different backgrounds

00:30:36.360 --> 00:30:42.660
and so on, the better it will be. So the results 
will really depend on, on the users who want to

00:30:42.660 --> 00:30:50.400
test. We already have, um, quite a lot of testers. I 
think, at least, over 100 organizations have, have

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:56.160
said that they would like to to join the 
testing phase, but we are always welcoming

00:30:56.160 --> 00:31:05.580
more. So please do contact us. You can use my 
email, which is Susanna s-u-s-a-double n-a at funka.com.

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:12.840
And we also have a project website. It's not 
very active yet, because we don't have so much,

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:17.940
um, results yet to show, but we will 
be more active in this website

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:24.360
soon, I hope. So you're also welcome to 
follow the project on accessibilitycluster.com.

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:28.800
And with that, I'm open for questions.

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:41.040
[Roberto] Um, well thank you very much Susanna. 
We don't have a lot of questions, we

00:31:41.040 --> 00:31:49.440
have one main question at this moment. Is, is 
the next one. You mentioned you will develop

00:31:49.440 --> 00:31:56.160
new features, uh, do you have examples of 
what kind of features are good candidates?

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:04.440
[Susanna] Well, before we started testing them we don't 
know which ones are the best candidates. That's

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:10.380
really is the test - it's the 10 features that 
I talked about, and showed the slide. These are

00:32:10.380 --> 00:32:16.080
the features that we are now testing, and if 
they all turn out not to work, or not to be,

00:32:17.160 --> 00:32:21.420
um, of interest for web authors, then we will 
have to come up with new ones. Because we have

00:32:21.420 --> 00:32:25.200
promised the European commission who 
is funding this that we are going to,

00:32:26.040 --> 00:32:35.400
um, to promote or provide 10 - at least 10 features 
when, when the project is ready. But as we are

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:41.040
just starting the testing phase, I can't tell you 
which one is the best candidate right now. We are

00:32:41.040 --> 00:32:48.240
testing all the 10 features, and then hopefully 
many of them will be good enough to present to

00:32:48.240 --> 00:32:55.320
the world. And if not, we will have to have make 
another round, and uh, yeah create new ones.

00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:04.380
[Robert] Cool, thank you very much. Well, at this moment 
we don't have any other questions. Is there

00:33:04.380 --> 00:33:11.280
anything that you want to add on this couple of 
minutes? Uh, you didn't cover on your presentation?

00:33:11.280 --> 00:33:17.040
You have, like, another five minutes if 
you have anything, or we can make a break.

00:33:19.500 --> 00:33:25.740
[Susanna] I think I'm, I, I hope that people will connect 
with us, and I'm happy to answer any question

00:33:25.740 --> 00:33:32.400
via email or Twitter, or just reach out to 
